More and more people are being asked by parents who want to watch their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to look for cars, can also be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases, such as the small Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of matches but will soon be the size of a watch.
The small Anicka case has stirred up a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracers in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of poor use of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of someone who is not aware, but I have not yet met such cases."
"The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons, add Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in the event of an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to carry something of this kind on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something explicitly when they don't want to be under control.'
"The mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long wait," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very questionable.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything to ensure that the child has no electronic device to locate it."
"Actually, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," the psychologist said.
It also recognizes that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, who offers tracking services for both cars and people, he says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the case of an assault.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on a regular basis after a given period."
"In case the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
'The most expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately indicates the position of the person who has slipped and is in an extended position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, mobile phones called intelligents who are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after they have formed it with a special prologial.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to the ones that are worn in pendant of the size of a box of lighters or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina from Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed as a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of GPS position acquisition systems (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
