Men with a longer index than the ring are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of hormone male testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple risk test for prostate cancer, especially for men before 60 years of age," the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University, proclaimed.
