These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarometer survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it follows the changes in attitude in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's survey in September and early October.
The first is the fairly sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its major institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South American Pacific (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
