The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
People must go to Visa Applicants Service centres prior to their interview with the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedure for the processing of visas at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to appear at Visa Applicants' Service Centres (ASCs) before their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will provide some benefits for the applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, there will be no need to make a payment for an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for visas of traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visas will not have to appear at an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the CSA, applicants who wish a second meeting to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants to the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service rate of $26.
For further information on the new procedure to apply for the visa, visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bolets/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
