A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
The United Nations proposed yesterday to Cancún a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gases (GES) which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact ampoules or, better, by bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED"), most of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the global car park's emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, large issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have engaged in voluntary reduction plans that are expected to move global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will still need to be subtracted from this balance of 5 gt to stabilize by 2020 the rise of the climate at 2 centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact ampoules, energy spending is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new light bulbs in DEL, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company has also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rhéostats as well as emit very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have posted reservations in the area of fluocompact ampoules as they contain mercury and they need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except if the manufacturers put in place a record.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather the coal thermal plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity spent in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and 8 million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction costs 2.5 billion.
